Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cafard was in danger, does that mean he feels scared too?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have feelings.
But how can we verify that it is the same when it is the same as us?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of replies to the question "What do you think is true without being able to have the evidence?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of conscience without me or anyone else who has so far been able to prove it, as we cannot prove that other human beings have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and approach the questions of feeling or in general of consciousness, we will enter difficult-to-practice fields because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he does death, escape, or attack.
Human beings behave in the same way, so some scientists draw a comparable subjective life from it.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transformation of our subjective life to that of the animals difficult.
One aspect is that circuits associated with human consciousness are almost always included in the frontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in the short-term memory and in management and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and appears to be completely absent in other beings.
So, at least for these aspects of our conscience, which depends on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from the other primates.
Another significant particularity could reside in the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence is linked to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness was not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is so difficult to determine what the consciousness of other animals can look like.
If this, internal and subjective, is neither measured nor, because of this particular hardware, analysed based on our own experience, then its observation poses serious problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious life, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
