The first time this happens can surprise you, but actually it doesn't matter.
It's a blessed variation in sleep that's called sleepiness.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course there's more than one who talks during the night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadic (once in life, for example, associated with a severe fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing more.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often linked to other sleep alterations such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (infant pipe to bed) or somnabulism, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very strong fevers, stress situations or overexcitement.
Anyway, it's a little bit of a studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or otherwise with screams, tears, long speeches ...
If sleepiness becomes very common, it would be fair to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes much anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We said that it is a welcome alteration, so there is no treatment, unless it is related to another alteration in sleep that can be treated (e.g. if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What you can do is take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, find quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have the pain of relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm themselves inside.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the dreams appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember no more than what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'll wake him up.
Even if he's talking, he's asleep and he's resting.
Remember that if he becomes very anxious several times, he is advised to consult a doctor or to check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not have the temptation to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because you're sleeping, he's not aware to be able to organize his mind.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, suddenly pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can question him during the night to know his secrets.
It's not even fun.
This causes much anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
