The interview - From safe red blood
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that had been seriously shaken by the scandal of blood contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the horror of the public, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, only 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
With efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before she proudly stated that in early 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, maintains that "trust is something extremely fragile."
On 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been seen in Europe, which has been holding the strong since its founding in 1998.
"And we did not know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which, when unknown and which can result from a serious disease, the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a brain degeneracy that inevitably leads to death, has been excluded.
In April 1999, therefore, the blood of those who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
But a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: nuclear acid (TAN) tests that directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the donor blood, not anti-virus antibodies, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed for a short period of motion, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our technicians, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has significantly reduced the risk of some donors being infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, a person of 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV- contaminated blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission occurs with a blood product.
I believe that today we can feel at ease with receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says Hema-Québec's head of management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen is going to emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
Hema-Quebec must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to security supplies, Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supplies.
"The needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to be recharged in red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the blood donors network, which is only on average 3% of the Québecs eligible for the blood donation."
However, every healthy person, aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria may give blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of those who offer their blood are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is present, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Poverty is very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and cannot give any more of their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so frenzied, it's rarely the time to spend an hour giving his blood," says Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec which also manages the only public blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was now considered a biomedical waste is a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the launch of our thousand blood sample of cordon and is expected to take more than a thousand per year.
We should begin to propose it for graffiti at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Decary, who describes this program of cord blood collection as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed that they can't have access there," because Hema-Québec has no means to offer this complex and costly program in all Québec hospitals.
