Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has attempted a six-million-dollar campaign against three authors and a small editing house without the sound in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
No surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would it be to ruin anyone or to support a position contrary to his own?
No matter the outcome of the trial, the authors and editor of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defenses and fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the pockets almost without the bottom of the mine.
The tactics, in these unequal struggles, are often to ruin the defenders in order to impose a settlement to the friend who will crush the opposition in addition to defraying anyone who will dare to rethink the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in the public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is happening in many countries where Barrick Gold is working, discussions in Canada are usually carried out by exchange of ideas and not by hits.
It was therefore sufficient for the mine to open its books, its files and establish a real debate through newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent research teams that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust the public opinion and rejects petition and letter of support from the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while ignoring the views of the same public?
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word refers only to the lawyers who are paid a lot rather than all the Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or you don't want to understand - Barrick Gold is that the public who supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does it first because it rejects the brutal way of the mine.
This public is willing to hear and judge Barrick, but on the basis of civilized exchange of arguments, and not as a result of what many perceive as a continuation of the belloon (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has, moreover, lodged a stay at the site of the Black Canada authors in an attempt to stop the use of that term...).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's continuation is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in block, the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis for intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that move the world's rich businesses into a country like Canada, with repetitive prosecutions, who can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so in accordance with the scientific standards used by the Black Canada authors.
She has a right to replicate.
The university environment in which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disputes and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's unbiased pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit such abuses.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agreed
The Bush administration and the congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, have finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic saving plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has been draining Wall Street for months is still to be buried by both Houses of Congress.
It provides, inter alia, for better control by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, and a right to look at the salaries paid to the directors of the securitised companies.
The US Secretary of Treasury, Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said the director of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to expose the real economy and the ordinary Americans of the current Wall Street crisis," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do so, trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to sprint in the last few hours in fear of the effect that would lead to a new failure on investors' mood.
The deadline for the opening of the markets this morning was the time limit.
In late negotiations, the two candidates to the US presidential election proved rather favourable to the agreement, but they failed to express their discontent that they were forced to reach this end.
Democrat Senator Barack Obama has been awarded the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that to allow owners to keep their home and the salary of the heads of companies rescued by the State.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibleness of some, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the waves of American television.
Asked about another channel to know if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The great lines I've read [showing] that this is something we're all going to have to digest and with which we're going to be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700-billion plan aims to purchase with taxpayers' money suspicious, risky and inventable loans from US financial institutions.
It occurs after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the outbreak of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (repressed) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and triggering a liquidity freeze and the disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican electors who had led the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to be out of this impasse since the Democrats have accepted that some "toxic" assets of the companies in difficulty are only provided by the government rather than purchased.
In order to round the corners of the world in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government had to lose for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its deployment.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of 250 billion to which 100 other billion will be added if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion should be entered by another vote of the Congress.
In exchange for his assistance, Washington will receive shares in the securitised companies that will be worth dividends to him in case of profit and that he will be able to sell again when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the arrest procedures for housing related to the real estate loans concerned by this plan, and to set limits on the remuneration and compensation paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives from today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have green light.
Votes have indeed continued to rise against this project yesterday, both in the Republican and Democrat camp.
"Of course Washington doesn't mean you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, at the address of his electors.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is to benefit taxpayers."
Animator of a small group in Congress named "the Caucus of Sceptics", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel Prizes, have written us to say: we are asked not to press and carefully examine the way to take it," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion).
The intervention of the Governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas indicated that it had refused to acquire its full-fledged competitor since it lost EUR 2 billion (2.9 billion) in the United States' crisis of real estate loans.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is part of the twenty-largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not about lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, there is a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It's just something that savers and households now appreciate that times are predicting uncertainty."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Manche, the British government seemed to nationalize another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would resume all current loans at Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the UK bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize from the beginning of this financial crisis.
