Overfill psychology: why do we spend more money?
In the course of sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be separated during this type of competition, such as a sale to auctions on eBay, and that is why they prefer to pay too high a price.
These research tried to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" with the help of sales to experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, while the other group participated in a sale to the gaming auctions, while with the help of a functional magnetic resonance process (IRMf), researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the sale of the auctions, an essential element of which is the overload of a third, the whole being under the brain trunk, called striatum, was moving intensely during the loss of the part.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "auto-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise of prices is explained by the escape from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economics members of this group of researchers continued to carry out financial surveillance analyses.
In these cases, three groups faced a partner, under different circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning the party, then they would receive 15 additional dollars, in return.
While the third group received these 15 dollars before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed on one on victory, while on the other on failure.
By proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the team of players "against failure" were available for higher positions than those performed by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any already existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them did not explain the phenomena found during sales to the auctions but by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by now, on a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of Economic Science at the University of New York, noted.
Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
One hundred miles are estimated to be the patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles follow a treatment. This is because the patients often do not know that they are carrying the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are mainly propagated in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is strongly recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by a bad general condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then, on the skin and on the white eye a visible yellowish, the cells become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Throughout the world, every year a million people die from the most severe form of this pathology, such as cancer or hepatic cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only one patient in ten receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to a cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus because pathogen destroys the liver cells in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing tests.
Pollution is much higher than the average of a population of three groups: people who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, 200 million patients with type C chronic hepatitis in the world are counted.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is recommended that you consult your doctor after you have observed symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
On September 30, the World Hepatitis Day was first organized by the bodies representing the four-foot disease groups in the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver caused by viruses, to the causes of its development and to the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
British daily Telegraph has published an article that says that researchers at Oxford University have made an interesting experience to analyze the extent to which belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of human being.
As part of this experience for at least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electrochocs, while each observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude a large part of suffering.
Thanks to a human brain palpation technique, Catholics have also been able to activate part of their brain responsible for pain control.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments involving academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experience takes place in the following way: an instrument that emits fibers and disseminates electrochocs is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to look at two paintings in a supportive way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady at the hermine painted by Leonardo de Vinci in the 15th century.
Researchers from the origins of this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of faith among believers, while the choice of the painting of Da Vinci, not very different from the first, brought on its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an IRM scanner, and during this time they received 20 electrochocs in four successive parts, while looking at either the painting on a religious theme or the painting on a more general theme.
The Catholics said that in the view of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "safe", as if one of them were "careful" and they were "slow, and peace invaded them".
In view of their religious theme painting, they reported 12% of their pain unless they looked at Leonard's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the experience himself, thinks that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in the athetes, provided that you find the right photo.
"We should find an image in which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, bishop of England, welcomed the results of these research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, effectively change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, it is no longer the question of what would be the effect on the control of the pain of the subjects if we showed believers a Madonna painted by Leonard or a painter of the same caliber?
Would the view of a better-quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
