The Smart Car Imitates the Flights of the Bourdon
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, the one with the bees.
In the amazing project presented at the CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the Burdonian bees gave the strategic idea of leaving the engineers at Nissan to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacles detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot, a bio-inspired auto-robotized system, of type BR23C, which he equipped with bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In its flights, each bee is its own space, in oval form, which, in fact, looks much like our safe protective helmet - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the department of research and development and technological public relations of the brand.
The bee facet eye plays a key role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the facet eye functions, engineers have considered the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the ship's microprocessor, which transforms it into an immediate process.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a second fraction. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
In contrast to any existing system at present, this avoiding manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
"If not, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must respond instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and the most internal layer of the protection envelope, a layer where the collision is currently considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that have the bees to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, acceleration and slowing as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentration is larger, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is primary, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should treat only a few incoming signals per second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. Thus, it uses only a few dozen kilo-octets of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a giga-octets capacity, or even mega-octets.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology used for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its entry into the series cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its integration into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his path.
