Industrial prices continued to increase
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent over the previous month, and 12.9 per cent over the month of August 2007 - reported by the Central Statistics Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to those of a previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export price fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have grown only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry were only slightly higher than 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with firstly, the production of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials have resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 per cent).
This has resulted in a decline in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), and in a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase of between 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent an important weight in national industrial exploitation, prices have increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, these are the prices of the oil processing sector that have experienced the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the manufacture of metallurgical products, an increase in prices of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the important area of food, beverages and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions were made in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the transformation industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 per cent during the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent of the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocation, in August, these are investment profit-initiating sectors that have shown the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the production sectors of consumer goods, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent processing did not undergo any change compared with the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase was observed in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent transformation (16.8%).
In the sectors of production of consumer goods, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors it was reduced by 1.4 per cent.
Sales prices in the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
