Mp3 player with fingertips, they risk hearing.
Listening to full-volume music for a longer period using portable music devices such as Mp3 readers may cause permanent injury to the audience.
This is what the European Commission, which, in a communiqué published in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks of the EU (Csseri), published today.
"of this scientific report - we read in the note - 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than an hour per day and per week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that a large number of young people who often use portable musical devices and mobile phones in full volume can inadvertently damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"Scientific data indicate that the responsible is at clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make public information available.
In addition, we need to review existing systems of control in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can monitor new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"Scientists-conclusion the Executive U- Confirms that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable and similar musical devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of musical devices to 100Db, but the concern increases with regard to auditory damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as lower levels and noise exposure time.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits for maximum noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for extended periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This affects 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 million and 10 million people in the U.S.
