Bye-bye to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities feed on the historic halls.
The historical cinema halls are fermented in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the stager Giuseppe Tornatore shows well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provinces,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of large multi-rooms, and the death of the consumption of mono-rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems unelectable and unquestionable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and charged with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of road and so much emotion," observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film offering to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, who told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia in a way of living the movie, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: these past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the halls of the main cities that paid the costs mainly: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is headed with 82 single rooms lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the event of the multiplex, as these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-story cinemas: 195 screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observed Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a room closes in a city, these frequencies are not all necessarily willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the missing deliberation of the credit for traders: the State's previous debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is a shame that, from a ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not comply with existing laws.
To support the sector, between EUR 16 million and EUR 18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, worried about these closures, has decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mary and Anec, the first such in Italy, to defend and promote mono cinemas in historical and peripheral centres.
Among the regulations envisaged, there are tax incentives for managers and benefits for the mobility public: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parking.
"It is an initiative that I am pleased to see," observed Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is obvious, however, that, in contrast to the superpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Paradise cinema" which I had been thinking of for 10 years.
I've been going to Rome for 25 years, and when I go to Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I've lived so much with shared emotions, I'm on the other side, so I don't see the dark panels through the dust.
